 succeeded in 0ms:
     1	# Fix: Lock TOCTOU → fcntl.flock
     2	
     3	## Problem
     4	
     5	`FileLockManager.acquire()` at `src/unison/lock.py:57-72` has a TOCTOU race. Between reading the lock file (line 58) and writing our PID (line 72), a concurrent process can read the same stale state — both believe they acquired the lock and both overwrite it.
     6	
     7	Additionally, the current `FileLockManager` supports multiple simultaneous project locks (see `test_multiple_projects`). The initial `self._fd` design only tracks one fd, so acquiring a second lock would overwrite the first fd and leak the first lock's descriptor.
     8	
     9	## Solution
    10	
    11	Replace the check-then-write pattern with `fcntl.flock(fd, LOCK_EX | LOCK_NB)`:
    12	- **`LOCK_EX`** — kernel-enforced exclusive lock; only one process holds it at a time.
    13	- **`LOCK_NB`** — non-blocking; returns immediately with `BlockingIOError` if the lock is already held.
    14	- **Auto-released** on process exit or file-descriptor close — no stale-lock cleanup needed.
    15	
    16	Track fds per-project in a `self._fds: dict[str, int]` to support multiple concurrent locks.
    17	
    18	## Fallback
    19	
    20	On platforms without `fcntl` (Windows), keep the current PID-based check-then-write behavior as a best-effort fallback.
    21	
    22	## Stale lock handling
    23	
    24	With `flock`, stale locks are eliminated: the kernel releases the lock when the process exits. The PID-in-file becomes metadata only (for diagnostics via `is_locked`).
    25	
    26	## Acceptance Criteria
    27	
    28	- `acquire()` uses `flock` on Linux/macOS; falls back to PID check on Windows.
    29	- `release()` unlocks via `flock` + unlinks the lock file, keyed by project.
    30	- All 16 lock tests pass unchanged (`pytest tests/test_lock.py -q`).
    31	- `is_locked()` continues to work for diagnostics.
    32	- Multiple simultaneous project locks are supported (dict of fds, not a single fd).

